      <hedline>
        <hl1>Yielding to Turkey</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Letter from Eugene T Rossides, American Hellenic Institute, says Americans should be disturbed that Clinton administration has capitulated to pressure by Turkey and then prevailed upon Congress to do same, in matter of measure condemning Turks' killing of Armenians (Oct 20 article)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>''House Backs Off on Condemning Turks' Killing of Armenians'' (news article, Oct. 20) revealed an extraordinary setback for American diplomatic credibility. Whatever one's individual views about the Armenian genocide issue, all Americans should be disturbed that the Clinton administration has capitulated to pressure by a foreign state and then prevailed upon Congress to do the same.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>''House Backs Off on Condemning Turks' Killing of Armenians'' (news article, Oct. 20) revealed an extraordinary setback for American diplomatic credibility. Whatever one's individual views about the Armenian genocide issue, all Americans should be disturbed that the Clinton administration has capitulated to pressure by a foreign state and then prevailed upon Congress to do the same.</p>
        <p>The administration's surrender to Turkey's belligerence has sent a clear message to the world: duress, threats and bluster work. All those who wish this country ill will duly take note.</p>
        <p>EUGENE T. ROSSIDES  Washington, Oct. 20, 2000</p>
        <p>The writer is general counsel, American Hellenic Institute.</p>
      </block>
